05370nam a22006015i 9780822390251DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20072007ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223902517 a10.1515/97808223902512doi  a(DE-B1597)553695  a(OCoLC)1224278838  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aHQ1154b.D34 2007 7aSOC0280002bisacsh1 aDavis, Kathy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Making of Our Bodies, Ourselves :bHow Feminism Travels across Borders /cKathy Davis; Robyn Wiegman, Caren Kaplan, Inderpal Grewal. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2007] 4cÂ©2007  a1 online resource (296 p.) :b38 illustrations, 3 tables, 3 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNext Wave: New Directions in Women's Studies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. The Book and Its Travels -- t1 OBOS in the United States: The Enigma of a Feminist "Success Story" -- t2 OBOS Abroad: From "Center" to "Periphery" and Back -- tPart II. Feminist Politics of Knowledge -- t3 Between Empowerment and Bewitchment: The Myth of the Boston Women's Health Book Collective -- t4 Reclaiming Women's Bodies: Colonialist Trope or Critical Epistemology? -- t5 Creating Feminist Subjects: The Reader and the Text -- tPart III. Transnational Body/Politics -- t6 Oppositional Translations and Imagined Communities: Adapting OBOS -- t7 Transnational Knowledges, Transnational Politics -- tAppendix 1. Foreign-Language Editions of OBOS -- tAppendix 2. Books Inspired by OBOS -- tAppendix 3. Translations and Adaptations of OBOS in Progress -- tAppendix 4. Translations and Adaptations of OBOS Seeking Funds for Start-up -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe book Our Bodies, Ourselves is a feminist success story. Selling more than four million copies since its debut in 1970, it has challenged medical dogmas about women's bodies and sexuality, shaped health care policies, energized the reproductive rights movement, and stimulated medical research on women's health. The book has influenced how generations of U.S. women feel about their bodies and health. Our Bodies, Ourselves has also had a whole life outside the United States. It has been taken up, translated, and adapted by women across the globe, inspiring more than thirty foreign language editions.Kathy Davis tells the story of this remarkable book's global circulation. Based on interviews with members of the Boston Women's Health Book Collective, the group of women who created Our Bodies, Ourselves, as well as responses to the book from readers, and discussions with translators from Latin America, Egypt, Thailand, China, Eastern Europe, Francophone Africa, and many other countries and regions, Davis shows why Our Bodies, Ourselves could never have been so influential if it had been just a popular manual on women's health. It was precisely the book's distinctive epistemology, inviting women to use their own experiences as resources for producing situated, critical knowledge about their bodies and health, that allowed the book to speak to so many women within and outside the United States. Davis provides a grounded analysis of how feminist knowledge and political practice actually travel, and she shows how the process of transforming Our Bodies, Ourselves offers a glimpse of a truly transnational feminism, one that joins the acknowledgment of difference and diversity among women in different locations with critical reflexivity and political empowerment.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aFeminismvCross-cultural studies. 0aSocial changevCross-cultural studies. 0aWomenxHealth and hygienevCross-cultural